<h1>Phase 1: Installing kernel module and tools.</h1>

<p>This page describes how to install AKARI's kernel module and userland tools.</p>

<hr>

<h2>Step 1: Installing kernel module</h2>

<p>Install a kernel development package which was configured with LSM (Linux Security Modules) support enabled (i.e. CONFIG_SECURITY=y ), and goto the extracted directory.</p>

<table border="1">
<tr><td>RedHat distributions</td><td>
# VERSION=`uname -r`<br>
# yum -y install kernel-devel-${VERSION}<br>
# cd /usr/src/kernels/linux-headers-${VERSION}*/
</td></tr>
<tr><td>Debian distributions</td><td>
# VERSION=`uname -r`<br>
# apt-get -y install linux-headers-${VERSION}<br>
# cd /usr/src/linux-headers-${VERSION}/
</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Next, run the following commands in order to install AKARI's kernel module.</p>

<table border="1">
<tr><td>
# wget -O akari.tar.gz 'http://sourceforge.jp/projects/akari/svn/view/trunk/akari.tar.gz?root=akari&amp;view=tar'<br>
# tar -zxf akari.tar.gz<br>
# make SUBDIRS=akari modules<br>
# make SUBDIRS=akari modules_install<br>
# depmod ${VERSION}
</td></tr>
</table>

<hr>

<h2>Step 2: Installing tools</h2>

<p>Run the following commands in order to install tools.</p>

<table border="1">
<tr><td>
# wget -O tools.tar.gz 'http://sourceforge.jp/projects/akari/svn/view/trunk/tools.tar.gz?root=akari&amp;view=tar'<br>
# tar -zxf tools.tar.gz<br>
# cd tools/<br>
# make -s<br>
# make -s install
</td></tr>
</table>

<hr>

<h2>Step 3: Updating boot configuration</h2>

<p>Add init=/sbin/akari-init parameter to the kernel command line. An example is shown below.</p>

<table border="1">
<tr><td>Before</td><td>
title CentOS (2.6.18-194.11.4.el5)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;root (hd0,0)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;kernel /boot/vmlinuz-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5 ro root=LABEL=/<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;initrd /boot/initrd-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5.img
</td></tr>
<tr><td>After</td><td>
title CentOS (2.6.18-194.11.4.el5)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;root (hd0,0)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;kernel /boot/vmlinuz-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5 ro root=LABEL=/ init=/sbin/akari-init<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;initrd /boot/initrd-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5.img
</td></tr>
</table>

<p>Although AKARI is a LSM module, AKARI can coexist with other LSM modules. But you need to add selinux=0 like below if you disable SELinux by specifying SELINUX=disabled in /etc/selinux/config . This is because /sbin/init unregisters LSM hooks which AKARI module depends on if SELINUX=disabled is specified in /etc/selinux/config .</p>

<table border="1">
<tr><td>Before</td><td>
title CentOS (2.6.18-194.11.4.el5)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;root (hd0,0)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;kernel /boot/vmlinuz-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5 ro root=LABEL=/<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;initrd /boot/initrd-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5.img
</td></tr>
<tr><td>After</td><td>
title CentOS (2.6.18-194.11.4.el5)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;root (hd0,0)<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;kernel /boot/vmlinuz-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5 ro root=LABEL=/ selinux=0 init=/sbin/akari-init<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;initrd /boot/initrd-2.6.18-194.11.4.el5.img
</td></tr>
</table>

<p>To uninstall AKARI, remove init=/sbin/akari-init parameter from the kernel command line and reboot the system.</p>

